BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Idle Muse Theatre Company Presents "The Three Musketeers"
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260403T200000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260403T200000
UID:260324zEUqNDiBsEmxHoqj_FKdQQ
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/505PC55KG0GXlUkpl7LDeg.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Idle Muse Theatre Company launches its 20th anniversary season
  with The Three Musketeers\, March 26 - April 25\, written by Robert Kauzl
 aric\, directed by Idle Muse Artistic Director Evan Jackson adapted from t
 he novel by Alexandre Dumas and originally commissioned for the 2010 Illin
 ois Shakespeare Festival\, at The Edge Off-Broadway Theater\, 1133 W Catal
 pa Ave. \n\nIdle Muse celebrates 20 years of productions with The Three M
 usketeers. Based on Alexander Dumas’s celebrated 1844 novel\, the Jeff A
 ward-winning Robert Kauzlaric adapts the French tale of swashbuckling intr
 igue\, adventure and fellowship as newly-minted musketeer D’Artagnan and
  the famous “three inseparables\,” Athos\, Porthos and Aramis take on 
 the machinations of a scheming cardinal and his minions.\n\nThe performanc
 e schedule is Thursdays\, Fridays and Saturdays at 8 p.m. and Sundays at 3
  p.m.\, with an added Wednesday performance on April 22 at 8 p.m. General 
 admission tickets are now on sale for $30 and $20 for seniors and students
  with $50 “pay it forward” tickets that assist in subsidizing tickets 
 for those who may not be able to access the production otherwise. Tickets 
 and additional group discounts are available at IdleMuse.org or the Idle M
 use Theatre Company Box Office\, 773.340.9438.
LOCATION:The Edge Off-Broadway
URL:https://cityspark.com/calendar/#!/show?location=Evanston,+IL&distance=
 5#/details/idle-muse-theatre-company-presents-the-three-musketeers/1818109
 7/2026-04-03T20
X-SOURCE:CitySpark Evanston
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:A BRIEF HISTORY OF CHASING STORMS (2025) with Curtis Miller & Robi
 n Tanamachi
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260403T190000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260403T213000
UID:260324VDA_Cbd8306H06Qyhpl85Q
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/2y-ABePV1U2P8DyhhhWrKA.large.png
DESCRIPTION:Details: A BRIEF HISTORY OF CHASING STORMS \\(2025\\) with Cur
 tis Miller & Robin Tanamachi   RSVP  A BRIEF HISTORY OF CHASING STORMS \\(
 Curtis Miller\, 2025\, 70 min\, Digital\\) As both a witty\, digressive es
 say film and an American road movie\, A BRIEF HISTORY OF CHASING STORMS ex
 plores the way that tornadoes and other extreme weather events shape the g
 eography and the cultural identity of the Midwest. Miller's travels across
  the Great Plain region take him from areas devastated during the 1970 mul
 ti-vortex tornado in Lubbock\, Texas\, to a TWISTER-themed museum exhibit 
 in the small town of Wakita\, Oklahoma\, and a myriad of impacted sites al
 ong the way. Through encounters with amateur meteorologists\, local histor
 ians\, elected officials\, and storm-shelter salesmen\, Miller subtly inte
 rrogates what it means to make images in the eye of the storm and how thos
 e images live on in collective memory for years after. This program will b
 e introduced by Robin Tanamachi\, atmospheric scientist who specializes in
  radar-based studies of severe storms and tornadoes\, storm chaser\, and A
 ssociate Professor in the Department of Earth\, Atmospheric\, and Planetar
 y Sciences at Purdue University. Following the screening\, filmmaker Curti
 s Miller \\(Lecturer in Art\, Theory\, Practice at Northwestern University
 \\)\, will participate in a Q&A with the audience. About the guest speaker
 s: Curtis Miller is a filmmaker and artist based in Chicago\, IL. His work
  often takes the American Midwest as both site and subject. His films have
  screened internationally at Visions du Réel\, IDFA\, DMZ Docs\, Glasgow 
 Short Film Festival\, Alchemy Film and Moving Image Festival\, Antimatter\
 , EXiS\, and the Chicago International Film Festival\, as well as the Hyde
  Park Arts Center\, Gallery 400\, and the Renaissance Society\, among othe
 rs. In 2025\, he was named one of Filmmaker Magazine's "25 New Faces of In
 dependent Film." A Brief History of Chasing Storms is Miller's first featu
 re. Robin Tanamachi is a research meteorologist and Associate Professor in
  the Department of Earth\, Atmospheric\, and Planetary Sciences at Purdue 
 University. She specializes in radar-based studies of severe storms and to
 rnadoes\, numerical analysis\, and atmospheric science education research.
  Robin has participated in numerous research studies\, including VORTEX2 a
 nd VORTEX-SE. Science on Screen: Watching the Weather Supported by the Slo
 an Foundation and the Coolidge Corner Cinema's Science on Screen program\,
  each of the screenings in the "Watching the Weather" series will feature 
 extended introductions by scientists\, historians\, and scholars\, who wil
 l shed light on the themes and histories depicted on screen. An initiative
  of the COOLIDGE CORNER THEATRE\, with major support from the ALFRED P. SL
 OAN FOUNDATION.
LOCATION:The Block Museum
URL:https://www.blockmuseum.northwestern.edu/cinema/2026/a-brief-history-o
 f-chasing-storms-2025-with-curtis-miller-robin-tanamachi.html
X-SOURCE:CitySpark Evanston
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Rent
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260403T193000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260403T220000
UID:260319Nk5IjS7HIka0l44dmkEZrQ
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/uCv7Ek3Hq0ueBkCvcouYNg.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Lower East Side of New York City. End of the millennium. Mark 
 and Roger are roommates\, and they can’t afford rent \\(again\\). But th
 ey don’t let that stop them from enjoying life while they can. They find
  solace in their community of fellow artists and activists who are also tr
 ying to make ends meet as they struggle through life\, love\, their art\, 
 the AIDS crisis\, and paying \\(or not paying\\) rent. Jonathan Larson’s
  final musical still resonates today about the importance of trying to get
  your voice heard\, even if it seems no one is listening.\n\nOn Sunday Mar
 ch 29\, join us for a post-show discussion with Rent dramaturgs and visit
 ors from Chicago House on the history and current state of the AIDs crisis
 \, centered around the power of community care. The discussion includes re
 sources for people currently living with HIV/AIDs.\n\nOn Friday\, April 10
 \, join us for a post-show discussion with members of the cast and artisti
 c team of Rent.
LOCATION:Newhart Family Theatre
URL:https://cityspark.com/calendar/#!/show?location=Evanston,+IL&distance=
 5#/details/rent/18337008/2026-04-03T19
X-SOURCE:CitySpark Evanston
END:VEVENT
