SUMMARY:An Afternoon with Matthew Cordell
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260412T140000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260412T150000
UID:260326WMLiRwmTlEeYKcl9j2aX_g
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/LtbRwqmUG0mwObfJSvHNAw.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:The Book Stall \\(811 Elm Street in Winnetka\\) is thrilled t
 o host award-winning author and illustrator Matthew Cordell on Sunday\, 
 April 12 at 2:00 pm for a drawing demo and a discussion featuring his new 
 picture book\, 102! From Caldecott Medalist Matthew Cordell comes a cozy\
 , magical nighttime adventure\, where a child discovers the mysterious\, m
 iniature world beyond his bedroom walls. Delightfully sweet as it is fanta
 stic\, 102 seamlessly explores the values of curiosity\, kindness\, and 
 generosity. The simple yet profound conclusion shares a clever wink with r
 eaders\, encouraging them to believe the unbelievable. This book is perfe
 ct for kids ages 6 to 8. Mr. Cordell will be happy to sign his works!\n\nM
 atthew Cordell is the Caldecott Medal-winning author and illustrator of W
 olf in the Snow\, Evergreen\, Cornbread & Poppy\, Wish\, and Hello\, N
 eighbor!: The Kind and Caring World of Mister Rogers. He is also the illus
 trator of highly acclaimed children’s books such as Every Dog in the Ne
 ighborhood \\(by Philip C. Stead\\)\, Bob\, Not Bob! \\(by Audrey Verni
 ck and Liz Garton Scanlon\\)\, and Leeva at Last \\(by Sara Pennypacker\\
 ). His books have been best-of-the-year selections by The New York Times\
 , The Boston Globe\, and NPR\, and have been translated into numerous lan
 guages around the world. Matthew lives in suburban Chicago with his wife\,
  author Julie Halpern\, and their two children.
LOCATION:The Book Stall
URL:https://thebookstall.com/event/2026-04-12/afternoon-matthew-cordell
X-SOURCE:CitySpark Evanston
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Music Of The Baroque: Vivaldi & Friends
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260412T193000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260412T213000
UID:260324UqZulWR8c02YFM0bUHHRHw
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/gkHDKQzxvUyGHYk6dCYCAA.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Italian violinist and conductor Fabio Biondi\, world-renowned 
 for “blazing\, fierce performances” \\(Washington Classical Review\\) 
 with his ensemble Europa Galante\, brings his irrepressible energy to the 
 Orchestra as he leads a high-voltage program centered around Vivaldi\, tho
 se who inspired him \\(Geminiani and Corelli\\)\, and those he inspired\, 
 like Nardini and Pugnani. Concertmaster Gina DiBello joins Biondi for Viva
 ldi’s Concerto for 2 Violins in G Minor. Make new discoveries and hear f
 amiliar favorites afresh!\n\nVIVALDI | Concerto for Strings in G Minor\n\n
 SAMMARTINI | Sinfonia in F Major\n\nGEMINIANI | Concerto\, “La Follia”
  \\(Madness\\)\n\nCORELLI | Concerto Grosso in B-flat Major\, op. 6\, no. 
 11\n\nNARDINI | Concerto for Violin\, op. 1\, no. 1\n\nVIVALDI | Concerto 
 for 2 Violins in G Minor\n\nPUGNANI | Sinfonia in B-flat Major\n\nSUNDAY\,
  April 12\, at 7:30 PM\n\nNorth Shore Center for the Performing Arts\n\n95
 01 Skokie Blvd\, Skokie\n\nTickets: $59-$119 \\(price includes $9 handling
  fee\\)\n\nMusic of the Baroque Orchestra\n\nFabio Biondi\, conductor\n\nG
 ina DiBello\, violin
LOCATION:North Shore Center For The Performing Arts
URL:https://cityspark.com/calendar/#!/show?location=Evanston,+IL&distance=
 5#/details/music-of-the-baroque-vivaldi-friends/16855566/2026-04-12T19
X-SOURCE:CitySpark Evanston
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Northshore Concert Band: Story Tellers
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260412T150000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260412T170000
UID:260324Fa9MVnvbj0KbEWPoQABk6A
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/5BI1F6HFgkqbenemgcuV6w.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:This April\, the Northshore Concert Band invites audiences to 
 rediscover the wonder of childhood with Story Tellers\, an imaginative con
 cert program celebrating curiosity\, adventure\, and the magic of storytel
 ling through music.\n\nThe program opens with Adam Schoenberg’s Rise\, a
  powerful and uplifting work that reflects both hopeful beginnings and hea
 rtfelt farewells. With its vibrant orchestration and emotional depth\, Ris
 e feels less like a story being told and more like a life moment being sh
 ared. It sets the stage for an afternoon that explores the innocence\, joy
 \, and discovery of youth.\n\nPercy Grainger’s Children’s March follow
 s\, brings youthful exuberance to life with lilting melodies and boundless
  energy. Considered a cornerstone of wind band repertoire\, it carries lis
 teners “over the hills and far away.” The spirit of adventure continue
 s with selections from Joe Hisaishi’s beloved score to the animated film
  My Neighbor Totoro. Through vivid musical scenes\, the audience encounter
 s the cuddly Totoro\, the whimsical Catbus\, and the charming escapades of
  sisters Satsuki and Mei.\n\nThe concert journeys into the enchanting worl
 d of Hans Christian Andersen with Martin Ellerby’s Tales from Andersen. 
 This imaginative suite transforms classic fairy tales into colorful musica
 l vignettes\, including The Emperor’s New Clothes and The Snow Queen—t
 he timeless story that inspired Disney’s animated film Frozen.\n\nThe pr
 ogram concludes with selections from John Williams’ sweeping score to Fa
 r and Away. Blending Irish folk influences with the expansive spirit of th
 e American West\, the music propels a hopeful journey toward new beginning
 s.\n\nThrough beloved stories\, evocative melodies\, and vibrant orchestra
 tion\, Story Tellers invites audiences of all ages to see the world throug
 h the eyes of a child—full of wonder\, imagination\, and possibility.\n\
 nJoin us this April for Story Tellers and experience an unforgettable musi
 cal celebration of childhood\, discovery\, and the timeless power of story
 telling.\n\nAdam Schoenberg - Rise\n\nPercy Grainger - Children’s March\
 n\nJoe Hisaishi \\(arr. Goto\\) - My Neighbor Totoro\n\nMartin Ellerby - T
 ales from Andersen\n\nJohn Williams \\(arr. Lavender\\) - Far and Away\n\n
 Tickets are priced at $25 for adults\, $20 for seniors\, and $10 for stude
 nts/children. All seats are general admission. Group discounts are availab
 le for parties of 10 or more. Please visit northshoreband.org to purchase 
 tickets online through Eventbrite.\n\nStory Tellers\n\nApril 12\, 2026 | 3
 :00 pm\n\nPick-Staiger Concert Hall\n\nNorthwestern University\n\nEvanston
 \, IL\n\nAbout the Northshore Concert Band The Northshore Concert Band\, n
 ow in its 70th year\, is a premier community wind ensemble based in the Ch
 icago area. Dedicated to artistic excellence\, community engagement\, and 
 music education\, the ensemble performs a diverse repertoire ranging from 
 traditional wind band classics to contemporary works and beloved film scor
 es\, offering audiences inspiring musical experiences throughout the year.
LOCATION:Pick-Staiger Concert Hall
URL:https://northshoreband.org/april-2026
X-SOURCE:CitySpark Evanston
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Talks@EHC: Writing  and Re-writing Home: Evanston in Memoir
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260412T163000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260412T180000
UID:260324B0Jrbpx5WkmYukmwK57MLQ
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/q_lLO5Pcd0i0UOHqxwhW7Q.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:How do we remember our own past? How do we use language to exp
 lore our own relationship to places that are important to us? Join Evansto
 n writers Joanne Jacobson and Ann Hudson for a discussion of how Jacobson
 ’s trilogy of memoirs recall Evanston landmarks like the B&G diner\, the
  Evanshire Pharmacy\, and Lee Street Beach: their cheeseburgers and cherry
  Cokes\, perfume samplers and roasted nuts\, their textures of sand and su
 n. And we’ll explore how remembering and writing about Evanston—or any
  home—evolves and changes over one writer’s lifetime: how “memory”
  itself is written and re-written. FREE\; RSVP recommended.\n\nPart of Hom
 e: Evanston\, an exploration of what it means to make a home\, and feel at
  home\, in Evanston.
LOCATION:Evanston History Center
URL:https://cityspark.com/calendar/#!/show?location=Evanston,+IL&distance=
 5#/details/talks-ehc-writing-and-re-writing-home-evanston-in-memoir/182342
 63/2026-04-12T16
X-SOURCE:CitySpark Evanston
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Rent
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260412T140000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260412T163000
UID:260319rnS_B3mdJEmfXGkyN3fbpg
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/uCv7Ek3Hq0ueBkCvcouYNg.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Lower East Side of New York City. End of the millennium. Mark 
 and Roger are roommates\, and they can’t afford rent \\(again\\). But th
 ey don’t let that stop them from enjoying life while they can. They find
  solace in their community of fellow artists and activists who are also tr
 ying to make ends meet as they struggle through life\, love\, their art\, 
 the AIDS crisis\, and paying \\(or not paying\\) rent. Jonathan Larson’s
  final musical still resonates today about the importance of trying to get
  your voice heard\, even if it seems no one is listening.\n\nOn Sunday Mar
 ch 29\, join us for a post-show discussion with Rent dramaturgs and visit
 ors from Chicago House on the history and current state of the AIDs crisis
 \, centered around the power of community care. The discussion includes re
 sources for people currently living with HIV/AIDs.\n\nOn Friday\, April 10
 \, join us for a post-show discussion with members of the cast and artisti
 c team of Rent.
LOCATION:Newhart Family Theatre
URL:https://cityspark.com/calendar/#!/show?location=Evanston,+IL&distance=
 5#/details/rent/18337008/2026-04-12T14
X-SOURCE:CitySpark Evanston
END:VEVENT
