BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Story Sessions & Big Shoulders Stories present: Cooler By the Lake
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260519T193000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260519T193000
UID:260221LoIP6cLReE-E1JQFKXKQdg
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/o0ODt1_Hjk6f-PSa-YvpdQ.large.png
DESCRIPTION:Experience Chicagos most powerful stories\, told by the people
  who are shaping its future. Cooler By the Lake brings together community 
 builders\, activists\, and creatives for an unforgettable night of live st
 orytelling. These arent just true tales\, theyre sparks of transformation 
 from the hearts of those making a difference. Authentic\, emotional\, some
 times hilarious\, and deeply human\, this show proves that storytelling is
  the heartbeat of our city. Produced in collaboration by Jill Howe is the 
 producer and founder of Story Sessions\, a live storytelling series with r
 eal-time illustrations\, since 2013. She has performed widely across Chica
 goland\, served as a resident storyteller at the Field Museum\, led storyt
 elling workshops for Newberry Library\, and presented a Naperville Tedx Ta
 lk on vulnerability. Find more of her work at jillhowe.com Suzy Kahn Weinb
 erg is the founder and executive producer of Big Shoulders Stories\, a sto
 rytelling production company launched in 2019 to elevate and amplify the v
 oices of the people and organizations who work to change communities in Ch
 icago. Suzy is also a co-producer of the long running monthly storytelling
  show\, Is this a thing? now in its 12 year.
LOCATION:Evanston SPACE
URL:https://cityspark.com/calendar/#!/show?location=Evanston,+IL&distance=
 5#/details/story-sessions-big-shoulders-stories-present-cooler-by-the-lake
 /18170733/2026-05-19T19
X-SOURCE:CitySpark Evanston
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Talks@EHC The History of Chicago Homes\, and What They Need Now
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260519T183000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260519T200000
UID:2603028SrV81-bDECEBXNwhw2pFg
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/D5VfS93h6UCSofSNbwhnEw.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Older Chicagoland homes were built to solve the problems of ye
 sterday\, but what do they need to thrive today? Join American Vintage Hom
 e for an engaging look at Chicago-area home history and the current homeow
 ner challenges that older buildings often present. What was the reason for
  common original design choices such as radiators under windows\, galvaniz
 ed pipe\, and basements? How can the average homeowner address the challen
 ges that these same features create today\, such as inefficient heat loss\
 , inconsistent moisture\, airflow and air quality issues\, and aging syste
 ms that lead to water quality issues? We’ll focus on what the average ho
 meowner can realistically do to preserve the character of older homes whil
 e improving comfort and efficiency. With Vicki Parker and Cornelius Muszcz
 ynski in partnership with American Vintage Home Community Education Series
 . FREE\, RSVP recommended.\n\nPart of Home: Evanston\, an exploration of w
 hat it means to make a home\, and feel at home\, in Evanston.
LOCATION:Evanston History Center
URL:https://cityspark.com/calendar/#!/show?location=Evanston,+IL&distance=
 5#/details/talks-ehc-the-history-of-chicago-homes-and-what-they-need-now/1
 8234353/2026-05-19T18
X-SOURCE:CitySpark Evanston
END:VEVENT
